        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/15678",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Another way to solve this without breaking the interface is to add the class namespace as an element in the options array:\n\nUsage:\n{code}\n$db = Zend_Db::factory('MyAdapter', array(\n    'username' => 'bill', \/\/ and other parameters\n    'adapterNamespace' => 'MyClasses'\n);\n{code}\n\nCode in the {{Zend_Db::factory()}} method:\n{code}\nif (isset($config['adapterNamespace'])) {\n    $namespace = $config['adapterNamespace'];\n    unset($config['adapterNamespace']);\n} else {\n    $namespace = 'Zend_Db_Adapter';\n}\n$adapterName = str_replace(' ', '_' , ucwords(str_replace('_', ' ', strtolower( $namespace . '_' . $adapterName))));\n{code}\n\nIt is not obvious how this change reduces the number of classes in an application.  In fact, it is a general rule that in almost every instance of stating that something is obvious, it is not.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-07-03T10:59:27.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-07-03T10:59:27.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/15680",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=zendfw",
                        "name": "zendfw",
                        "displayName": "Shekar Reddy",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "The default is to use something like Zend_Db_Adapter_Pdo_Mysql class that comes with the framework by specifying 'pdo_mysql' as the adapter name. If I subclass this adapter class with something like Widgets_Db_Adapter_Pdo_Mysql, there is currently no way to use my class instead of the default framework class because 'Zend_Db_Adapter_' namespace is prefixed to the adapter name in a hardcoded way.  At present, I'm creating a subclass of Zend_Db just to be able to use my adapter class which seems an overkill just to specify a different adapter class. The above change would elegantly offer the ability to use a different adapter class instead of the default and I don't need to use an extension of Zend_Db either - I can use Zend_Db straight and get rid of the subclass of Zend_Db. It reduces one file and one class in the application.\n\nHowever, your approach to using the options array for the namespace is more ideal :)\n\nPlease go ahead...\n\nThanks!\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=zendfw",
                        "name": "zendfw",
                        "displayName": "Shekar Reddy",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-07-03T13:28:46.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-07-03T13:28:46.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/15681",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "For what it's worth, you're right that currently there is no way to use the {{factory()}} method to instantiate your custom adapter classes outside the Zend_Db_Adapter namespace, but there is a way to use them:\n\n{code}\n$db = new Widgets_Db_Adapter_Pdo_Mysql($config);\n{code}\n\nUsing the {{factory()}} method is a convenience, but it is not required.  It does make things handy, though, if you want to specify the adapter class in a config file for your application.  I commonly do this:\n\n{code}\n$config = new Zend_Config_Ini(...);\n$db = Zend_Db::factory($config->database->adapter, $config->database->params->toArray());\n{code}\n\nThis of course does not work for user-supplied adapters unless the factory method accepts an alternative adapter namespace.  So I think this feature is a good one.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-07-03T13:44:53.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-07-03T13:44:53.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/16126",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
